  "prompt": "I saw this guy that disappeared on me four months ago and he's acting like nothing ever happened. What should I do?",
  "response": "Okay, this is a frustrating situation. It's completely understandable that you're feeling confused, hurt, and maybe even angry. Here's a breakdown of how to approach this, considering different possibilities and your desired outcome:\n\n**1. Acknowledge Your Feelings:**\n\n*   **You're allowed to be upset.** Don't minimize what you're feeling. Being ghosted and then having someone reappear acting like it's no big deal is disrespectful.\n*   **Identify your emotions:** Are you angry, hurt, confused, curious, or a combination? Understanding your feelings will help you communicate them more effectively.\n\n**2. Decide What You Want:**\n\nBefore you react, consider what you want from this interaction. Do you want:\n\n*   **An explanation?** Do you need to know *why* he disappeared?\n*   **An apology?** Do you want him to acknowledge he hurt you?\n*   **To re-establish a connection?** Are you open to trying to rebuild the relationship, even if cautiously?\n*   **Closure?** Do you simply want to tell him how his actions affected you and then move on?\n*   **To avoid him altogether?** Are you perfectly content with never speaking to him again?\n\nYour answer to this question will heavily influence your next steps.\n\n**3. Choose Your Approach:**\n\nHere are a few options, ranging from direct to indirect:\n\n*   **Option A: Direct Confrontation (If you want an explanation or apology):**\n\n    *   **When to use:** If you're feeling strong and ready to handle whatever he says, and if you genuinely want to understand his perspective (even if you don't agree with it).\n    *   **How to do it:** \"Hey, it's good to see you, but I'm a little confused. The last time we spoke was four months ago, and then you disappeared. I'd really appreciate it if you could explain what happened.\" Or, \"Hey, I'm glad we ran into each other, but I need to be honest, I was hurt when you stopped talking to me a few months ago without any explanation. Can you tell me what was going on?\"\n    *   **Important considerations:**\n        *   **Be prepared for excuses or defensiveness.** He might not be honest or forthcoming.\n        *   **Set boundaries:** If he becomes dismissive or disrespectful, you can end the conversation. \"I'm not going to continue this conversation if you're going to be [rude/dismissive/etc.].\"\n        *   **Focus on \"I\" statements:** Frame your feelings from your perspective. \"I felt hurt when...\" instead of \"You made me feel...\"\n\n*   **Option B: Casual but Direct (If you're cautiously open to reconnecting but need answers first):**\n\n    *   **When to use:** If you're curious but not invested, and want to gauge his reaction before getting too deep.\n    *   **How to do it:** \"Hey! Good to see you. Things got a little quiet there for a while, what were you up to?\" (Pay attention to his tone and body language when he answers). Or, \"Hey! It's been a while. I was wondering what happened back then.\"\n    *   **Important considerations:**\n        *   **Be prepared to cut the conversation short if you don't like his response.**\n        *   **Keep your expectations low.** He may still avoid giving a straight answer.\n\n*   **Option C: Indirect/Observe (If you're unsure or want to gather more information):**\n\n    *   **When to use:** If you're not ready for a direct confrontation, or if you want to see if he acknowledges the situation at all.\n    *   **How to do it:** Keep the conversation light and superficial. Observe his behavior and see if he brings up the disappearance himself. You could say something like, \"It's been a while, hasn't it?\" and see how he responds.\n    *   **Important considerations:**\n        *   **This might not provide you with the closure or answers you need.**\n        *   **Don't invest too much emotionally in this approach.**\n\n*   **Option D: Ignore/Avoid (If you want nothing to do with him):**\n\n    *   **When to use:** If you've decided you're better off without him in your life.\n    *   **How to do it:** Keep the interaction brief and polite, or simply excuse yourself and leave. \"Good to see you,\" and then move on.\n    *   **Important considerations:**\n        *   **This is perfectly valid.** You don't owe him anything.\n        *   **Be prepared to enforce your boundaries if he tries to engage you further.**\n\n**4. During the Conversation (Regardless of your approach):**\n\n*   **Stay calm:** As hard as it may be, try to remain composed. This will help you think clearly and communicate effectively.\n*   **Listen actively:** Pay attention to what he's saying (and *not* saying).\n*   **Trust your gut:** If something feels off, it probably is.\n*   **Don't let him gaslight you:** If he tries to deny what happened, minimize your feelings, or turn the blame on you, stand your ground.\n*   **Be prepared to walk away:** You are in control of the conversation. If it becomes too uncomfortable or unproductive, you can end it.\n\n**5. After the Interaction:**\n\n*   **Reflect:** Take some time to process what happened and how you feel.\n*   **Talk to a friend:** Sharing your experience with someone you trust can be helpful.\n*   **Don't overthink:** Once you've said your piece (or chosen not to), try to let it go. You can't control his behavior or his response.\n*   **Focus on your well-being:** Engage in activities that make you feel good and help you move forward.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **His reasons for disappearing might be complex.** He might have been dealing with personal issues, fear of commitment, or simply a lack of interest. None of these excuses the behavior, but understanding the possibilities can help you process it.\n*   **You deserve respect.** Ghosting is a disrespectful way to end a relationship (or potential relationship). Don't settle for someone who doesn't value your feelings.\n*   **Protect yourself.** Be careful about opening yourself up to someone who has already shown a lack of consideration for your feelings.\n\nUltimately, the best course of action depends on your personality, your goals, and your comfort level. Choose the approach that feels right for you and prioritize your own well-being. Good luck! You've got this.\n",
